Global buyers of commodities are on track to pay producers $5.2 trillion more in 2022 than they did in 2019 thanks to surging prices. That increase is the equivalent of 5% of world gross domestic product. In a scenario where forward prices for the second half of this year materialize, buyers would be paying $6.3 trillion more than during 2019, or 6.2% of GDP. In either case, such a shock would be on the scale of what the world experienced during the early 1970s oil crisis, when taken as a share of global GDP
